We also plot the heat maps of the initial and final energies with respect to the ionization potential (Fig. 1) for these two anion-solvent pairs. We find that there is a distinction between anion-solvent pairs for which the anion is oxidized, and those for which the solvent is oxidized. For the (TFSI−, PC) pair, the anion is oxidized. In this case, for configurations with IP near the average value, the configuration’s initial and final energies are near the average of their respective distributions. For configurations corresponding to the lower end of the IP distribution, their initial energy is high relative to the set of all configurations and their final energy is low. Inversely, configurations with high IP have below average initial energy but high final energies. Considering the (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
